            <div class="clear"></div>  
                
            <div class="normaltext">
                <p>The cost of photovoltaic systems is steadily decreasing.  The cost trends are very well understood, and are a function of scale of the industry as well as time period.  It is expected that most of the parts of the world will achieve grid parity by 2020, while certain regions of the world have already attained grid parity. Grid parity is a phenomenon where the cost of solar power becomes equivalent to the cost of conventionally generated power.  India is expected to reach grid parity around 2017-18.  It is after grid parity that the solar industry is expected to aggressively penetrate the market.  The acceleration towards grid parity in order to expedite mainstream penetration of solar technology into the energy sector drives many governments to incentivize and deploy at an early stage. Solar power has already achieved grid parity in a few states like commercial customers of Delhi, Gujarat, Mumbai, etc.</p>
                   
            </div> 
