            <div class="clear"></div>    
            
            <div class="headerglobal"> 
                <p>3.4 Gujarat Scenario</p>
            </div>
              
            <div class="clear"></div>  
                
            <div class="normaltext">
                <p>In a scenario, when new discoveries in energy sector are waiting to be commercially exploited by industrial sector and when India is forging ahead towards a renewable energy (RE) based economy, Gujarat is taking the leading in renewable energy and primarily in solar.</p>

<p>Gujarat leads the country in the per capita consumption of electricity. Going forward, Gujarat is planning huge investments to accelerate stronger economic momentum. The projected industrialization levels with increase in urbanization and standard of living which would lead to substantially higher demand for power. The energy units required in the next decade would be nearly two and half times the existing generation. Gujarat also has a large untapped potential for renewable energy basically solar energy which needs proper and efficient exploitation.</p>

<p>Gujarat&rsquo;s performance on power front has been the best as it has been able to achieve zero per cent normal power deficit and nil peak power deficits in several years because of good grid management. As of November 2016, Gujarat had a total installed power generation capacity of 30,324.56 MW.</p>

<p>In a recent report of the 40 state-owned power distribution companies (Discoms) that the Mistry of Power, Government of India, audited for annual financial and operational performance, the four Discoms of Gujarat have topped the list, for the fourth year in a row.As per the report, no other Discoms in the country have got an A+ rating except the four Discoms of Gujarat.</p>
 
            </div> 
                
            <div class="clear"></div>    
            
            <div class="headerglobal"> 
                <p>3.5 Gujarat Solar Policy 2015</p>
            </div>
              
            <div class="clear"></div>  
                
            <div class="normaltext">
                <p>Government of Gujar in in 2015 notified the solar policy with an objective to increase generation of green energy. It is aimed at promoting several modes of generation, including roof-top solar power for house/building owners, distribution of solar-powered pumps to farmers and standalone photo-voltaic (PV) systems for domestic use.</p>

<p>The state will facilitate de-centralised and off-grid solar applications to meet various energy requirements for domestic purpose, according to an official release.</p>

<p>For those living in remote areas, where regular grid-based connection is not feasible, the Government will initiate schemes for basic home lighting using PV system. The salient features of the Solar Policy for captive and rooftop solar PV system are listed below:</p>

<ol>
  <li>For distributed generation promotion through net metering mechanism, the solar photovoltaic installation size has been capped at 50% of the sanctioned load of the power consumer.</li>
  <li>Any excess power generated by a rooftop PV system will be bought by the distribution company at Average Pooled Power Cost (APPC).</li>
  <li>Banking of excess energy will be allowed for one billing cycle.</li>
  <li>Transmission charges and losses, wheeling charges and losses and demand cut are not applicable on energy generated by rooftop solar PV systems.</li>
  <li>For electricity generated by rooftop solar PV systems in Gujarat, no electricity duty will be applicable. The generated solar power is also exempt from Cross subsidy surcharge and additional surcharge.</li>
</ol>

 
            </div>
              
            
            <div class="clear"></div>    
            
            <div class="headerglobal"> 
                <p>3.6 Solar Power as a Solution to Indian Power Industry</p>
            </div>
              
            <div class="clear"></div>  
                
            <div class="normaltext">
                <p>PV is progressively becoming more attractive, vis-a-vis other renewable sources of power, as its cost declines. The various factors leading to decline in cost includes setting up of large scale plants, integration across the value chain, declining cost of raw material, reducing material consumption and higher efficiency of modules.</p>

<p>Due to its proximity to the equator, India receives abundant sunlight throughout the year. Solar PV solution has the potential to transform the lives of 450 million people, who rely on highly subsidized kerosene oil and other fuels, primarily to light up their homes. Renewable energy source is a practical solution to address the persistent demand supply gap in the power industry.</p>

<p>The following features of solar power make it the most viable renewable source of energy for India:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Solar energy is available in abundance</li>
  <li>Available across the country &ndash; unlike other renewable sources, which have geographical limitations</li>
  <li>Available throughout the year</li>
  <li>Decentralized / off-grid applications &ndash; addressing rural electrification issues</li>
  <li>Modularity and scalability</li>
</ul>

<p class="titlesection">Merits of the Solar PV Plant:</p>

<ol class="lowerroman">
  <li>Power from the sun is clean, silent, abundant and free.</li>
  <li>Photovoltaic process releases no CO2, SO2 or NO2 gases during energy generation, which are normally associated with burning finite fossil fuel reserves and don&rsquo;t contribute to global warming.</li>
  <li>Photovoltaics are now a proven technology which is inherently safe as opposed to other fossil fuel based electricity generating technologies.</li>
  <li>No fuel is required for generation, so fuel cost of power generation is zero</li>
  <li>Solar power shall augment the needs of peak power needs</li>
  <li>Solar Powered Grid Connect Plants can act as tail end energizers, which in turn reduces the transmission and distribution losses.</li>
  <li>Solar Power can be set up on barren / unproductive land with reasonable sun radiations. Solar PV plant&nbsp; do not require large Water source or effluent disposal system as required in the case of conventional thermal plants.</li>
  <li>Generation of electricity from Solar PV is totally free of Green House Gas emission.</li>
  <li>Routine O&amp;M cost is comparatively very less.</li>
  <li>Man power Requirement is very less.</li>
</ol>
<div class="page-break"></div>
<p class="titlesection">Demerits of Solar PV Power Plant:</p>

<ol class="lowerroman">
  <li>Initial capital cost is very high compared to any other conventional technology.</li>
  <li>Low capacity utilization factor typically in the range of 16 to 20 %.</li>
  <li>Large area of land required.</li>
  <li>Cost of power generation per kWh is very high compared to conventional plants.</li>
  <li>There are only a few manufacturers of PV module in India with large capacity.</li>
  <li>Technology is changing very fast there by chances of obsoleteness remains high.</li>
  <li>With the launch of JNNSM, the relevance and advantages shall be brought in to a sharper focus to meet the energy demand in an elegant and clean way. The PV approach is particularly suited for the geographical and socio-economic features of this country having highly skewed energy distribution between urban and rural areas. Special provisions under JNNSM are expected to accelerate the growth of PV industry and make India emerge brightly in the global PV scenario.</li>
</ol>

 
            </div>    
               
            <div class="clear"></div>    
            
            <div class="headerglobal"> 
                <p>3.7 Conclusion</p>
            </div>
              
            <div class="clear"></div>  
                
            <div class="normaltext">
                <p>In conclusion, the global solar market is exponentially increasing at a rate of 40% per annum, which is based on various national and state-level initiatives scattered around the world.&nbsp; Such high growth rates are a characteristic of a developing market before reaching a steady growth rate.&nbsp; The deployment of solar technologies is mainly contingent on policies, where the main drivers are generation-based or capital subsidies as well as renewable purchase obligations. The REC mechanism is a novel but promising mechanism in India in its juvenile stages, but has proved to be successful around the world to meet renewable purchase obligations. At the present scenario MNRE/SECI has proposed capital based subsidy under various schemes from their Clean Energy Fund in order to reduce the cost of electricity per unit to the utilities. In addition, several state governments like Gujarat, Haryana, Punjab, MP, Telangana, AP, TN&nbsp; and others are also venturing into solar with innovative business models to optimize the cost of solar PV plant. The rooftop solar power plants are promoted across the country for the self-consumption of the customers. Hence, the favourable policy and the reduction in the cost of equipment are the one of the major drivers.</p>

