    </ol>
                </div>    
    
            
            <div class="clear"></div> 
                
            <div class="headerglobal"> 
                <p>6.1.1 South-facing roof</p>
            </div>
            <div class="normaltext">   
                <p>India being in the northern hemisphere the solar panel is to be installed facing south to maximize electricity generation. This placement allows panels to take full advantage of the sun’s path in the sky as the sun shines longest on a building’s south side. However, southeast- and southwest-facing panels will perform about 5 percent less efficiently.</p>
            </div> 
                
            <div class="clear"></div> 
                
            <div class="headerglobal"> 
                <p>6.1.2 Shadow free space on the roof</p>
            </div>
            <div class="normaltext">   
                <p>Further, Photovoltaic panels are very sensitive to shading. Any shading will dramatically reduce electricity generation. Installers use a Solar Pathfinder device to determine if there are shading concerns from trees (consider mature height), chimneys, nearby buildings, etc. Keep in mind the sun’s path changes throughout the year. For maximum electricity production, it is ensured the solar panels will be unshaded year-round (especially from 9 or 10 am until 3 pm).</p>
            </div> 
                
            <div class="clear"></div> 
             
            <div class="headerglobal"> 
                <p>6.1.3 Angle of the roof</p>
            </div>
            <div class="normaltext">   
                <p>Typically panels are mount directly (flush) on an existing south-facing roof for aesthetics. To maximize electricity generated year-round, mount modules at an angle equal to or close to your site’s latitude (28 degrees for Delhi; 12 degrees for Bangalore). Installers can tilt at an angle best for your site, system type, and electricity needs. For more summer electricity production, tilt at latitude minus 10 degrees to 15 degrees; for more winter production, tilt at latitude plus 15 degrees</p>
                <p>Flat Roofs: Panels can be angled on flat roofs often found on commercial, industrial, and institutional buildings, but should not be placed flat (horizontal) because of dust buildup that will block the sun.</p>
            </div>     
                
            <div class="clear"></div> 
            
            <div class="headerglobal"> 
                <p>6.1.4 Condition of Roof</p>
            </div>
            <div class="normaltext">   
                <p>Most roofs can safely support PV panels and mounting system weight. The rule of thumb is 2 to 5 pounds per square foot depending on the panel type and installation method. For example, a 320 watt crystalline panel (1.9m x 0.9 feet) weighs about 22.5 kg. An installer should determine if the roof/structure can handle the added weight. Innovative mounting systems can make panel removal easy, but because panels can last 25+ years, it may be less expensive and labor intensive to make needed roof repairs before installing panels.</p>
                <p>If your building fulfils the above-mentioned points or you can make adjustments wherever required, then your building or site is a good solar electric system candidate! A more detailed assessment of your roof is discussed further in the report. </p>
            </div>        
                
            <div class="clear"></div> 
                
